+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
+++++ Pb_S_Cl_fromdatabases +++++
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

These examples retrieve from databases all compounds within the Pb-S-Cl phase diagram from 
databases.
(In the article Saleh, Manna "A Data-Driven Framework to Accelerate Semiconductor Discovery", 
these runs were used to retrieve all structures to be used for DFT simulations to buils a 
Pb-S-X phase diagram more accurate than that available in single databases)  
The same procedure can be adopted to build Pb-S-Br or Pb-S-I phase diagrams by changing the name of 
the halogen atom in the input files in all subfolders

HOW TO RUN 
(after having created and activated the IPSE_DB environment, see IPSE-DISCO manual):
0  - register on the Materials Project (MP) website, since to run MP inputs you need to insert 
     you own API key in the input file
1  - copy in the folder where IPSE-DISCO will be run the folder IPSE_DB_modules and the
     file IPSE_DB.py (from the GitHub repository main page)
2  - launch with python IPSE_DB.py <input file name> [<output file name>]
2b - optionally, the high-energy polymorphs can be excluded by running (linux synthax adopted 
     here, excluding polymorphs lying more than 0.15 eV/atom above the structural ground state):

     python filter_Eform.py -t 0.15 <name of the csv file created in step2> 
     chmod 755 remove_unstable.sh
     ./remove_unstable.sh
     
     note that filter_Eform.py can be found among the utilities of IPSE-DISCO, and 
     remove_unstable.sh is created by the filter_Eform code  




+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
++ ML-training_chalcohalides_oqmd_combo_features ++
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

In this example, a ML model is trained on a dataset composed by all halides, chalcogenides
and chalcohalides present in the oqmd database (see the Supporting Information of the article
by Saleh&Manna mentioned above for details). 
It adopts the best performing ML algorithm among those tested, namely Random Forest Regressor
with 600 estimators, 50% features considered for the best split, and no bootstrap. 
Feature analysis is also performed; to switch it off, change do_features_analysis=True 
to do_features_analysis=False in the input file.

HOW TO RUN
1  - copy in the running folder the following directory 
     and file from the IPSE-DISCO GitHub repository: 
     IPSE_ML_CH_modules/ IPSE_ML_main.py
2  - run with:
     python IPSE_ML_main.py > out &




+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
+++++ make_ConvexHull_from_database_and_ML ++
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

In this example, the conex hull for Pb-S-Cl (but also for Pb-S-Br and Pb-S-I by substituting 
the halogen name in input_IPSE_CH.py) are evaluated by combining data from the oqmd database
and from the ML model 

HOW TO RUN
0  - copy here (by 'here' we mean the folder where the code is run) the following directory 
     and two files from the IPSE-DISCO GitHub repository:
     IPSE_ML_CH_modules/ IPSE_CH_main.py IPSE_ML_main.py  
1  - copy here the two pkl files (scaler.pkl and ML_model.pkl) produced in the example 
     ML-training_chalcohalides_oqmd_combo_features [these pkl are to reproduce the results
     of the above mentioned article from Saleh&Manna, but clerly previosly trained ML model
     can be adopted; in this case, also copy the file input_IPSE_ML.py adopted to make those 
     pkl file]
2  - run with:
     python IPSE_CH_main.py  



